about how you got interested

00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:08.039
in this work and sort of how
you got to where you are today?

00:01:08.039 --> 00:01:10.330
GISELLE CARINO: Well, you
know, I grew up in Argentina,

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:11.600
in rural Argentina.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.940
And when I say
rural, I mean rural.

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:17.490
I remember receiving the
Sunday paper at 4:00 PM.

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:19.300
That's rural.

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:25.940
And I went to an
all-girls Catholic school.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:27.690
And this is not at all
a comment on faith.

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:32.882
As you just mentioned, we work
with progressive religious

00:01:32.882 --> 00:01:34.840
leaders, and I'm part of
the board of Catholics

00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:35.840
for the Right to Decide.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:40.637
But I remember we used to be
girls playing one side and boys

00:01:40.637 --> 00:01:41.720
playing on the other side.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:44.350
And I remember always asking
the question, why is this?

00:01:44.350 --> 00:01:47.890
I have brothers and cousins,
and we used to play together

00:01:47.890 --> 00:01:49.502
and things were different there.

00:01:49.502 --> 00:01:51.710
And I remember the answers
were not quite satisfying.

00:01:51.710 --> 00:01:54.647
And then, as I
grew up, my parents

00:01:54.647 --> 00:01:56.980
would say like, what do you
want to be when you grow up?

00:01:56.980 --> 00:02:01.680
And across the street, there was
a farming school full of boys,

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:05.020
and I thought that
was really cool.

00:02:05.020 --> 00:02:06.604
They used to be
outdoors all the time.

00:02:06.604 --> 00:02:08.020
And I said, I want
to be a farmer.

00:02:08.020 --> 00:02:09.280
I want to that school.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:12.440
And they would like,
hmm, not really.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:13.520
That's for boys.

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:15.160
And I was like, why is that?

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:18.012
And again, not a very
satisfying answer to that.

00:02:18.012 --> 00:02:19.720
And then, I think all
of it came together

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:23.830
when I was in secondary school
and one of my best friends

00:02:23.830 --> 00:02:24.760
got pregnant.

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:28.620
And she wasn't rejected
from our school,

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:33.010
but she couldn't be
part of us anymore.

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:35.560
The social stigma associated
with teen pregnancy is huge,

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:37.820
continues to be huge.

00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:40.060
And so I think all
of it came together,

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:42.960
and it was clear that it
could have been any of us.

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:45.940
That we needed the
information to be

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:48.649
able to protect ourselves,
to live healthy lives.

00:02:48.649 --> 00:02:49.690
And that it wasn't there.

00:02:49.690 --> 00:02:52.270
That wasn't available to us.

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:55.450
I also grew up you know during
the dictatorship in Argentina.

00:02:55.450 --> 00:02:59.630
I was born in 1976 in June.

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:01.660
Now you know my age.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:05.480
And the dictatorship began
in March of that year.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:09.970
So I remember that
crushing sense

00:03:09.970 --> 00:03:12.080
that things would never change.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:15.820
And then, when democracy
came, that feeling of it

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:18.340
was in our hands to make that
happen and to protect it.

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:22.394
So I think all of it
had to do with ending up

00:03:22.394 --> 00:03:24.560
in Planned Parenthood doing
work for women's rights.

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:28.570
I truly believe that there isn't
the possibility of development

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:31.946
without half of the
population being included.

00:03:31.946 --> 00:03:34.870
And sexual and public
health and rights are key.

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:36.430
Deciding if we want
to have children,

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.310
when we want to have
children, with whom

00:03:39.310 --> 00:03:45.080
is critical to us being fully
participants in society.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:46.544
So all came together there.

00:03:46.544 --> 00:03:47.710
DANIELLE BROWN: I love that.

00:03:47.710 --> 00:03:50.092
Well, thank you for sharing
