00:39:16.260 --> 00:39:18.600
but talk a little
bit about certainly

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:20.730
in the US over the
past several years

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:22.770
there's been a lot of
restrictive laws passed

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:26.720
making it harder to access
contraception, access

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:28.350
safe and legal abortion.

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:31.260
How does sort of the
policy in the United States

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:35.730
and the arguments and politics
sort of around women's health

00:39:35.730 --> 00:39:38.670
impact the work you
do in the region?

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:39.960
GISELLE CARINO: Yes.

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:42.990
The US used to be a
place where we looked up

00:39:42.990 --> 00:39:45.060
for leadership on these issues.

00:39:45.060 --> 00:39:47.250
And as I said, that's
no longer the case.

00:39:47.250 --> 00:39:51.500
But in addition to that, and
in addition to the global gag

00:39:51.500 --> 00:39:53.310
rule that I talked
before that really

00:39:53.310 --> 00:39:58.560
curtails the possibility of
organizations to serve women,

00:39:58.560 --> 00:40:00.450
I say that what we
are beginning to see

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:05.830
is a much stronger violent
and aggressive opposition

00:40:05.830 --> 00:40:07.730
in the region,
which is quite new.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:10.600
We had not seen that before.

00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:15.256
In a matter of a
few months, we had

00:40:15.256 --> 00:40:18.200
our offices vandalized
in one of the countries,

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:20.490
our executive director in
another country with death

00:40:20.490 --> 00:40:25.450
threats, and things that we
clearly had not seen before.

00:40:25.450 --> 00:40:28.300
We also have something that came
up in Colombia that is called

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:34.210
[? Agenda ?] [? Ideology, ?] a
whole reframing conversation.

00:40:34.210 --> 00:40:39.330
And it came right at the
moment of the peace process

00:40:39.330 --> 00:40:43.450
and against all of our
issues really very strongly.

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:49.420
And I think we have to think
about as a clear influence

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:51.860
there has been some
reports recently,

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:54.310
I think in "The
Guardian" about the role

00:40:54.310 --> 00:40:58.510
of the opposition in the
US funding the opposition

00:40:58.510 --> 00:41:01.680
in many of the Latin American
and Caribbean countries.

00:41:01.680 --> 00:41:05.680
And I think we are going to
see more of that in the years

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:06.502
to come.

00:41:06.502 --> 00:41:07.960
DANIELLE BROWN: So
really, the work

00:41:07.960 --> 00:41:09.970
we all do in our
individual regions

00:41:09.970 --> 00:41:12.070
and countries really
is interconnected.

00:41:12.070 --> 00:41:14.110
And so playing a
role to actively

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:17.140
advocate for policies that
advance women's health

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:18.477
are important for all of us.

00:41:18.477 --> 00:41:19.810
GISELLE CARINO: Yes, absolutely.

00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:20.779
Very much, very much.

